They are not just guesses but well-supported explanations that have stood the test of time and repeated experimentation. Observations, on the other hand, are the data collected through experiments, measurements, or direct sensory experience. They serve as the empirical evidence that either confirms or refutes the theories.

A theory is considered valid when it successfully predicts the outcomes of future observations. There are a few reasons why some things stick. One is repetition. If we keep practicing something, our brain strengthens the connections that help us remember it. Another is when something is important to us. If we care about something, our brain pays more attention to it and is more likely to remember it.

On the other hand, things that are not important or not practiced don't stick. Our brains have a limited capacity for memory, so if we don't use something often, it might fade away.
